The results hitherto arrived at may be summed up as follows :—

(i) That the later dest. are useless, and among them is to be included s, which should disappear from the list of first-class authorities.

(ii) That the three MSS. HTE, together with the lost W, and the fragments of P, are the only source of real knowledge.

(iii) That W was a gemellus of T, and therefore does not add to its authority.

(iv) That T is thesons delerz'orum.

(v) That E is a ‘mixed' MS„ agreeing in base with T, but cor- rected from H.

(vi) That in all probability H and T do not come from the same source.

(vii) That P is by no means infallible, and is too scanty to be accepted as an arbiter.

(viii) That many of the variants in the text go back to a remote antiquity.
